    "id": "aapl_equity_vol",
    "description": "AAPL equity SABR volatility surface calibrated from a 3×3 (expiry × strike) grid of OptionVol lognormal quotes, chained on a USD-OIS discount curve bootstrapped from deposit and IRS quotes in the same plan. Step 1 produces the USD-OIS discount curve; step 2 fits the vol surface against it. Snapshot data (AAPL spot price and quarterly dividend schedule) are supplied via initial_market.prices and initial_market.dividends — these are not bootstrappable and remain as legitimate snapshot inputs. This is the dependency-richest Phase 2 envelope: it demonstrates how Track A (discount curve) and Track B (equity spot, dividends, vol quotes) data are composed in a single envelope. The vol_surface step uses β=0.5 (the CEV backbone, widely used for equity) rather than β=1.0 (lognormal) because the engine's α-solver bound of 5.0 is incompatible with β=1 at large absolute equity strikes: for β=1 the ATM relationship is α ≈ σ_ATM×F ≈ 0.25×175=43.75, far exceeding the solver bound. With β=0.5, ATM α ≈ σ_ATM×√F ≈ 0.25×13.2=3.3, comfortably within bounds. SABR calibrates α/ν/ρ per expiry against a monotone put-skew smile (higher vol at low strikes, lower vol at high strikes). The quote grid is designed so that total variance is nearly linear in strike (ratio of mid-point variance to linear interpolation ≈ 0.985), ensuring the SABR-fitted surface passes the butterfly arbitrage check. fail_on_bad_fit is set to false because the vol_surface report uses config.solver.tolerance() (1e-12) as the residual threshold: even a perfectly converged SABR calibration produces vol residuals in decimal units (1e-2 scale) far above 1e-12, so the report always marks the step as failed regardless of calibration quality. This is a known mismatch between the solver-convergence tolerance and vol-residual scale. Strikes are absolute price levels (155, 175, 195) around the ATM spot of 175.0. The produced VolSurface is keyed as 'AAPL-EQUITY-VOL' and is retrievable via MarketContext::get_surface().",
